Introduction to Advanced Java

-Advanced Java is the part of Java programming used to develop web-based and enterprise applications. It provides technologies and APIs that allow Java programs to interact with databases, web servers, and network applications.
-Advanced Java is mainly used to build dynamic web applications. It works on top of Core Java and uses server-side technologies to create powerful and scalable applications.
-Some important technologies in Advanced Java include JDBC (Java Database Connectivity), Servlets, JSP (Java Server Pages), and frameworks that help in developing web applications.
-With the help of Advanced Java, developers can perform tasks such as database connectivity, web application development, session management, and server-side programming.

  In simple words, Core Java is used to build basic programs, while Advanced Java is used to build web and enterprise applications.
### ADVANCED JAVA – LEARNING ROADMAP

**Advanced Java** is used to develop **web applications, enterprise applications, and database-driven systems**. It is built on top of **Core Java** and mainly focuses on **server-side programming**.
---

## 1. Prerequisites (Before Advanced Java)
Before learning Advanced Java, we should know:

• Core Java basics
• OOP Concepts (Class, Object, Inheritance, Polymorphism, Abstraction, Encapsulation)
• Exception Handling
• Collections Framework
• File Handling
• Multithreading
---

## 2. Advanced Java Roadmap
### Step 1: JDBC (Java Database Connectivity)
JDBC is used to connect Java applications with databases.
Topics to learn:
• JDBC Architecture
• JDBC Drivers Types
• Steps to connect Java with Database
• Statement
• PreparedStatement
• CallableStatement
• ResultSet
• CRUD Operations (Insert, Update, Delete, Select)
---

### Step 2: Servlets
Servlets are Java programs that run on a **web server** and handle client requests.
Topics to learn:
• Servlet Architecture
• Servlet Life Cycle
• GenericServlet
• HttpServlet
• doGet() method
• doPost() method
• Request and Response objects
• ServletConfig
• ServletContext
• Session Management
---

### Step 3: JSP (Java Server Pages)
JSP is used to create **dynamic web pages**.
Topics to learn:
• JSP Life Cycle
• JSP Elements
• JSP Scriptlet
• JSP Expression
• JSP Declaration
• JSP Directives
• JSP Implicit Objects
• JSP Action Tags
---

### Step 4: Session Management
Session management is used to maintain user data between requests.
Types:
• Cookies
• URL Rewriting
• Hidden Fields
• HttpSession
---

### Step 5: MVC Architecture
MVC stands for:
• Model
• View
• Controller
This architecture is used to separate **business logic, presentation, and control logic** in web applications.
---
### Step 6: Frameworks (Next Level)
After Advanced Java basics, developers learn frameworks such as:
• Spring
• Spring Boot
• Hibernate
• REST API Development
---

## Simple Advanced Java Learning Flow
Core Java
↓
JDBC
↓
Servlets
↓
JSP
↓
Session Management
↓
MVC Architecture
↓
Spring / Spring Boot / Hibernate
↓
Full Stack Java Development

---

**Conclusion:**
Advanced Java helps developers build **dynamic, secure, and database-driven web applications** using technologies like **JDBC, Servlets, JSP, and modern frameworks**.
